{
  "answer": "**Two works in the corpus contain apostrophes (direct literary addresses) to inanimate objects.**\n\n**Cynewulf's *Andreas***: Andreas directly addresses a marble pillar (an inanimate stone), commanding it by God's decree to produce a miraculous flood upon the heathen city.[^1]\n\n**Unknown's *Old English Elegies*** (specifically \"The Wanderer\"): The wanderer laments the past through apostrophes to lost objects of earthly glory, such as \"Alas, the bright cup!\" (addressing a cup) and \"Alas, the prince's pride!\" (addressing an abstract quality made concrete).[^2]\n\nNo other works in the corpus contain such instances. Searches for common apostrophe phrases (e.g., \"O Death\", \"O Sea\") across English translations yielded no matches, and examinations of major poems (e.g., *Elene*, *Juliana*, *The Ruin*) found none.\n\n[^1]: Cynewulf, *Andreas*, [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-andreas-07b573/01/translation/#p-2e50c1).\n\n[^2]: Unknown, *Old English Elegies*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/translation/#p-9cca5e).",
